                   degradation. OM contents
  (CL {\textless} GL {\textless} FL {\textless} NL), H/C, O/C, C/N
  ratios, and OM oxidation states were significantly different between land use
  types in top- and subsoils. With decreasing bulk OM content, C was relatively
  depleted while H and particularly N were higher. The data suggest very high N
  mobilization rates from strongly decomposed peat in agricultural topsoil. A
  comparison to peat C and N from mostly intact peatlands of the Northern
  hemisphere reveals that agriculture and, to a lesser extent, forestry induce
  a progressed state of soil degradation.},
